            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>In the consulship of Marcus Magrius Bassus and Lucius Ragonius Quintianus, on the Ides of June, at Cumae in the temple of the Divine Vespasian, in the order of decurions, which the praetors Marcus Mallonius Undanus and Quintus Claudius Acilianus had summoned, the drafting committee selected by lot were Caelius Pannychus, Curtius Votivos and Cosidius Felicianus. The motion was out forward by the praetors about appointing a priest of the Mother Goddess of Baiae, in place of Restitus the sacerdos, who had died. It was unanimously decreed that Licinius Secundus should be the sacerdos. The quindecemviri sacris faciundis greet the praetors and other magistrates of Cumae. We have learned from your letter that you have created as priest of the Mother of the Gods Licinius Secundus in the place of the deceased Claudius Restitutus. By your will, we have permitted him the right to wear the armlet and crown, but only within the boundaries of your colony. We send good wishes to you. Pontius Gavius Maximus signed on behalf of the master of the college, on the 16th day before the Kalends of September, when Marcus Umbrius Primus and Titus Flavius Coelianus were consuls.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>As attested by this inscription, the temple of the divine Vespasian was still being used by the decurions in 289 CE, but was likely (originally) of a late first century CE date (c.95 CE).</p> <!-- Temple probably identified on long side of forum. Fears 1975, 6-7. -->
            </div>
